# Native Secure Enclave SSH keys on macOS 26+ (Tahoe). Apple's stock ssh signs with a
# Touch-ID-gated key held in the Secure Enclave via the built-in provider at
# /usr/lib/ssh-keychain.dylib — hardware-bound, no dongle, no third-party agent.
# SecurityKeyProvider only tells ssh HOW to sign; ssh finds the key itself at the default
# path ~/.ssh/id_ecdsa_sk, so there is no per-machine IdentityFile and this fragment is
# identical on every Mac. The `Match exec` gate applies it ONLY where the provider file
# exists, so on Linux and pre-Tahoe macOS `test -f` fails and nothing here takes effect.
#
# This is opinionated and needs one-time per-Mac setup (key generation + enrollment), and
# it has trade-offs (notably it overrides FIDO -sk keys on the same Mac). Full setup,
# assumptions, and gotchas: docs/ssh-secure-enclave.md
Match exec "test -f /usr/lib/ssh-keychain.dylib"
    SecurityKeyProvider /usr/lib/ssh-keychain.dylib
